title: Lorenz Butterfly
square_url: The archetypal strange attractor originally derived for atmospheric convection. Famous for illustrating the Butterfly Effect. Eq: dx/dt=σ(y-x)

title: Rössler Band
square_url: A simpler chaotic system containing a single manifold that folds into itself. Resembles a Mobius strip structure. Eq: dx/dt=-y-z

title: Thomas Cyclic
square_url: A cyclically symmetric attractor forming a complex lattice of interlocking loops. Often requires extensive support removal. Eq: dx/dt=sin(y)-bx

title: Halvorsen Knot
square_url: A chaotic system exhibiting cyclic symmetry. The trajectory visually resembles a "Borromean Ring" style knot. Eq: dx/dt=-ax-4y-4z-y^2

title: Chen Double Scroll
square_url: Similar to the Lorenz system but topologically more complex. Discovered in 1999 by Chen and Ueta. Eq: dx/dt=a(y-x)

title: Sprott Case A
square_url: A member of the Sprott alphabet of simple chaotic flows. Case A is known for its elegant simplicity and thin ribbon structure. Eq: dx/dt=y

title: Sprott Case B
square_url: Sprott Case B features a dual-lobe structure that mimics the Lorenz butterfly but with a simpler algebraic definition. Eq: dx/dt=yz

title: Gumowski-Mira
square_url: Actually a 2D map extruded into 3D. Often resembles marine life or jellyfish structures depending on parameters. Eq: x(n+1) = y(n) + a(1 - 0.05y(n)^2)y(n) + f(x(n))

title: Clifford Torus
square_url: A 4D torus projected into 3D space. The resulting shape creates a dense
dimensions: cloud-like volume of points. Eq: x(n+1) = sin(ay) + c*cos(ax)

title: Nose-Hoover

title: Rabinovich-Fabrikant
square_url: Known for its extremely complex
dimensions: wave-like trajectories that look like turbulent fluid flow. Very difficult to print without supports. Eq: dx/dt=y(z-1+x^2)+gx

title: Three-Scroll Unified
square_url: A generalized system capable of generating multiple scroll attractors. This variant features three distinct orbiting lobes. Eq: dx/dt=a(y-x)+dxz

title: Dadras
square_url: Discovered in 2010. Unique for its wide
dimensions: sweeping wings that resemble a manta ray in flight. Eq: dx/dt=y-ax+byz

title: Chen-Lee
square_url: A multi-wing attractor that evolved from the study of Euler equations for rigid body rotation. Eq: dx/dt=ax-yz

title: Bouali
square_url: A relatively new system (1999) known for robust chaos and limit cycles that look like two interlocked rings. Eq: dx/dt=x(4-y)+z

title: Finance
square_url: A chaotic model originally designed to simulate interest rates and investment demand. Visually sparse but structurally strong. Eq: dx/dt=(1/b-a)x+z+xy

title: Newton-Leipnik
square_url: Derived from Euler rigid body equations. Features two 'strange' attractors that coexist in the same phase space. Eq: dx/dt=-ax+y+10yz

title: Lu-Chen
square_url: The 'bridge' between the Lorenz and Chen systems. Shows the transition from simple butterfly wings to complex multi-scrolls. Eq: dx/dt=a(y-x)

title: Hadley
square_url: A model of atmospheric circulation. The shape is simpler and more 'contained' than Lorenz
dimensions: making it excellent for smaller prints. Eq: dx/dt=-y^2-z^2-ax+af

title: Burke-Shaw
square_url: A system that demonstrates a period-doubling route to chaos. The shape resembles a twisted heart or pretzel. Eq: dx/dt=-s(x+y)

title: Arneodo
square_url: A system specifically designed to find low-dimensional chaos. Visually distinct for its 'branching' structure. Eq: dx/dt=y
